AVONDALE, Ariz. (AP) — Kyle Busch bought what he thought was a safe life insurance plan that would provide self-funding income for his retirement. When Pacific Life Insurance Company sent a sixth premium notice on what was supposed to be a five-year payment plan — and most of the money he invested was gone — the two-time NASCAR Cup Series champion knew something was wrong. “I was like, wait a second, what am I getting a sixth-year premium payment for?” Busch said from Phoenix Raceway on Saturday. “We got on a call with the guy who sold me the premium policies and he ran me around in all these circles, couldn’t answer the questions, so I was like, this is fishy.” Once Busch and his wife Samantha realized something was wrong, they turned to an independent firm that found their policy would expire in 16 months and all of the $10.4 million they invested gone. freestar.queue.push(function () {
